## The Other Half of Implementation

Day 54 verified and documented the technical control implementations — encryption, authentication, audit logging, network security, WAF. Today completes the Task I-1 implementation work by verifying and documenting the administrative and operational controls.

The relationship between technical and administrative controls is not sequential — it is interdependent. The MFA technical control from Day 54 is only effective if the account provisioning procedure ensures MFA enrollment before account activation. The audit logging technical control only satisfies the HIPAA audit requirement if a defined process exists for reviewing those logs and responding to anomalies. The encryption technical control only maintains its integrity if the patch management procedure ensures that vulnerabilities in the encryption implementation are patched on schedule.

Administrative controls are what give technical controls operational continuity. Without them, technical controls drift — configurations change, accounts accumulate, logs go unreviewed, patches fall behind. The implementation verification for administrative controls is therefore asking a different question than Day 54's technical verification. For technical controls, the question was: is it configured? For administrative controls, the question is: is it operating — and is there evidence that it has been operating consistently?

---

## What I Worked On Today

Task I-1 administrative control implementation verification has the same structure as the technical verification: confirm each control is implemented as documented in the SSP, capture the implementation evidence, identify discrepancies, and document them as SSP update items or POA&M entries.

For administrative controls, implementation evidence is different from technical configuration screenshots. Evidence includes: approved policy documents with signatures and review dates, training completion records, procedure documents, review logs, test records, and similar operational documentation that demonstrates the control is being executed — not just that a document was written.

A written policy with no evidence of execution is not an implemented control. It is a planned control that needs to be operationalized before it can be assessed as implemented.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clarified administrative control implementation for me today is the distinction between a *policy* and an *implemented control*.

A policy document describes what should happen. An implemented control is a policy document plus evidence that what should happen is actually happening. The gap between those two states is the gap between paper security and operational security.

When I write a user provisioning procedure, I have produced a policy. When I can show provisioning request records, approval documentation, and account creation logs for the last ten accounts created — I have demonstrated an implemented control. When I can show that all ten accounts had MFA enrollment confirmed before access was activated — I have demonstrated that the technical and administrative controls are working together as intended.

This distinction is critical for NIST SP 800-53A assessment methodology. Assessors use three assessment methods: examine (review the document), interview (ask the responsible party about the process), and test (verify that the control produces the expected outcome). A policy document satisfies the examine method. Evidence of execution is needed to satisfy the interview and test methods. An administrative control that only has a document, with no execution evidence, will be assessed as partially implemented at best.

