**PS-4: Personnel Termination — Operational Status**

**SSP Description (from Day 51):** Account deactivated within 4 hours of HR separation notification. ISSO reviews audit log for 90 days preceding separation.

**Implementation Verification:**

Separation records review — five most recent employee separations:

| Separation | HR Notification Time | Account Deactivation Time | Time to Deactivation | 90-Day Audit Review |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | [date/time] | [date/time] | 2h 15m | Completed — no anomalies |
| 2 | [date/time] | [date/time] | 3h 45m | Completed — no anomalies |
| 3 | [date/time] | [date/time] | 1h 30m | Completed — one access event flagged, reviewed with supervisor, confirmed legitimate |
| 4 | [date/time] | [date/time] | 4h 10m | Completed — no anomalies |
| 5 | [date/time] | [date/time] | 2h 50m | Completed — no anomalies |

*Discrepancy:* Separation 4 exceeded the 4-hour deactivation target by 10 minutes. Review of the record found that the HR notification was received during a period when the ISSO was in a meeting without phone access — the notification sat unread for approximately 90 minutes before the ISSO acted. The 4-hour target was met by minutes.

This near-miss surfaces a process gap: the ISSO is the single point of failure for account deactivation. If the ISSO is unavailable (meeting, travel, illness), the 4-hour target may be missed. The SSP should document a backup — the IT Administrator as the designated secondary for account deactivation when the ISSO is unavailable. Adding this backup designation as a POA&M item.

*Verification Evidence:* Separation records with timestamps; audit log review documentation for each separation; POA&M entry for backup designation gap.

