**IR-3: Incident Response Testing — Tabletop Exercise Record**

**SSP Description (from Day 51):** Annual tabletop exercise with after-action report. Full technical simulation planned as POA&M item.

**Implementation Verification:**

Most recent tabletop exercise: conducted [date]. Scenario: ransomware attack on OpenMRS EC2 instance — simulating RS-001. Participants: ISSO, Health IT Manager, Compliance Officer, one clinical staff representative. Facilitated by ISSO.

After-action report: produced and reviewed. Key findings from the tabletop:

1. The clinical staff representative was not familiar with the manual patient registration process — confirmed the urgency of completing clinical downtime procedures (CP-2 POA&M item).
2. The Compliance Officer was uncertain about the 60-day vs. 72-hour notification timeline distinction — HIPAA breach notification is 60 days from discovery; individual HIPAA incident notifications to leadership are 24 hours per the IRP. This confusion was resolved during the tabletop debrief and the IRP has been clarified.
3. The process for declaring an incident formally — triggering the IR plan — was not well understood by non-security participants. Added a clear "declare incident" trigger step to the IRP as a result.

IRP was updated following the tabletop to incorporate the three findings. Updated version reflects tabletop date and revision notes. ✓

Full technical IR simulation remains a POA&M item. ✓

*Verification Evidence:* Tabletop exercise scenario document; participant sign-in; after-action report; IRP revision record showing changes made from tabletop findings.

