## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The AT-2 quarterly compliance review gap found today — training completion not checked on schedule, resulting in overdue users going undetected — reminded me of the circumstances that contributed to the **2014 Community Health Systems breach**, which I covered on Day 40 from the network architecture perspective.

Post-incident investigation of the CHS breach found that the organization had security policies and procedures in place — but their execution was inconsistent. The breach exploited a combination of technical vulnerabilities and gaps in the operational execution of security procedures, including monitoring processes that were not functioning as documented.

The CHS case illustrates a pattern that appears repeatedly in healthcare breach post-incident analyses: organizations have good security documents, but the operational discipline to execute those documents consistently — the quarterly reviews, the monthly log checks, the annual training confirmations — breaks down. The security program exists on paper but not in practice.

The AT-2 gap found today is a small-scale version of exactly this pattern. The quarterly compliance pull was not executed. Overdue training went undetected. The administrative control existed but was not operating. Discovering this gap through Task I-1 implementation verification — before the assessment, before a breach — is the intended outcome of honest implementation verification.

Adding the calendar reminder for quarterly compliance review is a five-minute process improvement. But the discipline of verifying that the review happens and documenting that it happened is what separates a security program that operates from one that only documents.

